# hilavitkutin-linking

Cross-platform dynamic library loading primitive. One layer above the
OS loader, one layer below the extension-host orchestration. Single
concern: open a shared library, resolve an explicit named symbol,
return a typed handle whose lifetime is bound to the loader.

The crate is `#![no_std]`. It pulls libc for Unix targets and
windows-sys for Windows targets. It does not depend on any other
hilavitkutin crate, not the engine, not the api, not the build-time
crate, and not the ecosystem crates. The three substrate dependencies
are notko for the fallibility ladder, arvo for numeric primitives, and
arvo-bits for boolean values.

Everything about extension descriptors, lifecycle stages, role
declaration, capability matching, failure policy, host orchestration,
or downstream domain contracts sits above this layer in
hilavitkutin-extensions or in consumer-specific contract crates such
as viola-plugin-abi. This crate is deliberately kept narrow so those
higher layers can be written or rewritten without churning the loader.

## Public items

Seven items make up the public surface:

- `Library` is the opaque loader handle. RAII closes the library on drop; `Library::close` is the explicit form that surfaces unload errors. Every `Symbol` or `StaticRef` resolved from a `Library` borrows it via a lifetime parameter.
- `Symbol` is the typed handle to a resolved function-pointer symbol. `T` is restricted by the sealed `LibrarySymbol` marker. `Symbol::get(&self) -> T` returns the function pointer by value.
- `StaticRef` is the typed handle to a resolved static-data symbol (the pointer-to-static-struct pattern every extension ABI uses for its descriptor export). `T: 'static` is arbitrary data. `StaticRef::get(&self) -> &T` dereferences the pointer.
- `LibrarySymbol` is a sealed marker trait over function pointer shapes. v1 admits `extern "C"` function pointers at arities zero through eight. Downstream crates cannot add new impls; the arity set covers realistic extension-ABI shapes.
- `LinkError` is the load / resolve / unload error enum. Fixed-shape variants; no heap payloads. Carries `arvo::USize` platform codes where relevant.
- `IncompatibilityError` is the narrow compatibility-check error enum. Three variants: version skew, arch mismatch, ABI mismatch.
- `compatibility_check` is the free function exposing the narrow compatibility hook colocated with `IncompatibilityError`.

## Shape

`Library::load(path)` opens a library given a null-terminated byte-slice path. The unix backend calls `dlopen(path, RTLD_NOW | RTLD_LOCAL)`. `RTLD_NOW` resolves all of the loaded library's external symbols at load time, surfacing missing-symbol errors immediately rather than at first call. `RTLD_LOCAL` keeps each cdylib's symbols private to the loading scope, so two simultaneously-loaded extensions cannot collide on `#[unsafe(no_mangle)]` symbols whose names happen to match (the trampolines emitted by `hilavitkutin-extensions-macros` rely on this isolation for the bound on their collision risk). On Linux glibc, `RTLD_LOCAL` is the default-when-neither-flag-given so the explicit flag is documentation; on macOS and the BSDs the documented default is `RTLD_GLOBAL` so the explicit flag is load-bearing. Two resolution methods then produce typed handles from that loader:

- `Library::resolve<F: LibrarySymbol>(&self, name)` resolves a function-pointer symbol into `Symbol<'_, F>`. `Symbol::get` returns the fn pointer by value via the `transmute_copy`-from-raw-pointer pattern that matches the platform loader's contract for function symbols.
- `Library::resolve_static<T: 'static>(&self, name)` resolves a static-data symbol into `StaticRef<'_, T>`. `StaticRef::get` dereferences the resolved pointer to `&T`. This is the pattern every extension ABI uses for its descriptor export.

Both handles expose `as_raw` as an escape hatch for cases outside the typed wrappers. The lifetime parameter `'lib` ties either handle to its source `Library`, so use-after-close is a compile-time error.

`Symbol` and `StaticRef` are deliberately separate types. The pointer reinterpretation rules differ: for function pointers the resolved address IS the function-pointer value (transmute); for static data the address is the location of a `T` (deref). Hiding the distinction behind a single type would force runtime branching or unsafe; two types keep the soundness explicit.

`Library::close(self)` explicitly unloads the library and returns `Outcome<(), LinkError>`. Dropping the `Library` achieves the same effect but discards any platform error at unload. Consumers that want to surface those errors call `close`.

Error shapes are fixed enum variants with no heap payloads. OS error codes are carried as `arvo::USize` values (non-negative on both unix errno and Windows GetLastError ranges). On Windows, `LinkError::LoadFailed { platform_code }` always reflects `GetLastError()` at the failure site. On Unix, the value is the thread-local `errno` read via the per-libc helper (`__errno_location` on Linux/Android, `__error` on Darwin and BSD); since POSIX does not require `dlopen` to set `errno`, the value is best-effort and reflects the most recent libc syscall failure during the load. On unsupported unixes (Solaris, Haiku, etc.) the value is `0`. `LinkError::PathEncodingUnsupported` distinguishes a path the loader cannot transcode from a path that the OS loader rejects after handoff. v1 fires it on Windows for non-ASCII paths and paths exceeding the classic `MAX_PATH` (260 wchars); Unix paths are opaque bytes and never produce it. Full UTF-8 to UTF-16 transcoding plus `\\?\` LongPath support is a separate scope.

## Architectural position

The loader sits at the bottom of the extension stack. Conceptually:

```
  consumer-specific contract crate (viola-plugin-abi, etc.)
  --------------------------------------------------------
  hilavitkutin-extensions  <-- domain-agnostic host orchestration
  --------------------------------------------------------
  hilavitkutin-linking  <-- this crate
  --------------------------------------------------------
  OS dynamic loader  (dlopen / LoadLibrary)
```

No hilavitkutin crate depends upward from this one. The engine itself never uses this crate. The engine is static composition. Dynamic linking through this crate exists strictly for downstream consumers (viola, future hosts) whose extension ecosystems use cdylib extensions.

## Dependencies

Workspace dependencies only:

- notko for Just / Maybe / Outcome primitives on public signatures.
- arvo for USize / Cap and similar numeric primitives where public signatures express sizes or capacities.
- arvo-bits for Bool where public signatures express boolean values.

Platform dependencies:

- libc under `cfg(unix)` for raw FFI bindings to dlopen / dlsym / dlclose.
- windows-sys under `cfg(windows)` for raw FFI bindings to LoadLibraryW / GetProcAddress / FreeLibrary under the minimal feature set.

Build-time dependency:

- mockspace (workspace convention) bootstraps the mock workflow via build.rs.

No dependency on hilavitkutin, hilavitkutin-api, hilavitkutin-build, hilavitkutin-ctx, hilavitkutin-persistence, hilavitkutin-str, or hilavitkutin-extensions. The linking layer is deliberately isolated.

## Platform coverage

v1 supports:

- macOS aarch64 and x86_64
- Linux x86_64 and aarch64
- Windows x86_64

Additional platforms can be added without changing the public API. wasm32 is explicitly out of scope. The model is different enough to warrant a separate transport.

## Arbitrary-time linking invariant

One non-negotiable assumption governs everything in this crate: any library can be loaded at any point in the host's execution, invoked immediately, and dropped at any time, independent of other libraries. The ABI, trait contracts, and typed symbol handle semantics all enforce this by construction.

No global registry exists. The host never reads a static "currently loaded libraries" collection; every handle is explicit. No init ordering is assumed. Libraries do not depend on other libraries being loaded first, and each loader handle is self-contained. The lifetime parameter on the typed symbol handle ties it to its loader, so dropping the loader at any time invalidates outstanding symbols at compile time. Lifecycle is strictly per-library, never ecosystem-wide: a consumer may load library A at time T, invoke it at T+1, drop it at T+2, load library B at T+3, and that is correct use.

The consumer-side obligation is that host code built on top of this crate tolerates arbitrary-time linking. Assumptions like "all libraries loaded before any invoked", "init ordering gates invocation", or "the full ecosystem must be known before proceeding" are forbidden at the framework level. Any consumer that needs ecosystem-wide semantics builds them in its own higher layer.

This invariant propagates forward into the upper host layer (`hilavitkutin-extensions`) and into any downstream consumer contract crate (`viola-plugin-abi`, and so on). Every layer in the stack preserves the invariant or explicitly documents the loss.

## Non-scope

This crate does not:

- Define extension descriptor shapes, role identifiers, or capability IDs. Those live in hilavitkutin-extensions and consumer contract crates.
- Scan linker sections for registration. `inventory`, `ctor`, `#[distributed_slice]`, `.init_array` discovery are all explicitly rejected. Discovery is pull-based only: the host asks for a named symbol; the library must export it.
- Parse descriptors, version strings, or capability sets. It exposes one narrow compatibility helper; all other parsing is above.
- Host or orchestrate lifecycle. Calling init / invoke / shutdown on a loaded extension is the consumer's responsibility.
- Support Rust `dylib` crate type. Only C-ABI `cdylib` extensions are loadable. This preserves the LLVM optimisation barrier and the Rust ABI stability boundary that the broader extension architecture requires.
- Provide async loading wrappers, telemetry, or signature verification in v1. Those are BACKLOG items.

## Origin and rename

This crate was introduced as `hilavitkutin-extensions` in design round 202604240745 (PR #34, merged 2026-04-24). Round 202604240615 renames it to `hilavitkutin-linking` and reclaims the `hilavitkutin-extensions` name for the host orchestration layer above it. The rename reflects that this crate mechanically performs runtime dynamic linking; the name "extensions" is better suited to the user-facing contract host above, which matches external vocabulary for IDE extensions and similar contract-bound unit systems.

